SIMPLE: stumble
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stumble
<hw>Stum"ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Stumbled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Stumbling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stumblen</ets>, <ets>stomblen</ets>; freq. of a word akin to E.
<ets>stammer</ets>. See <er>Stammer</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
trip in walking or in moving in any way with the legs; to strike the
foot so as to fall, or to endanger a fall; to stagger because of a false
step.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There <qex>stumble</qex> steeds strong and down go all.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The way of the wicked is as darkness: they know at what they
<qex>stumble</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. iv. 19.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To walk in an unsteady or clumsy manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>stumbled</qex> up the dark avenue.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To fall into a crime or an error; to err.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that loveth his brother abideth in the light, and there is none
occasion og <qex>stumbling</qex> in him.</q> <rj><qau>1 John ii.
10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To strike or happen (upon a person or thing) without
design; to fall or light by chance; -- with <xex>on</xex>,
<xex>upon</xex>, or <xex>against</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ovid <qex>stumbled</qex>, by some inadvertency, upon Livia in a
bath.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Forth as she waddled in the brake,⟦br⟧
A gray goose <qex>stumbled</qex> on a snake.</q> <rj><qau>C.
Smart.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stumble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stumble
<hw>Stum"ble</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to stumble
or trip.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To mislead; to confound; to perplex; to cause
to err or to fall.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>False and dazzling fires to <qex>stumble</qex> men.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One thing more <qex>stumbles</qex> me in the very foundation of
this hypothesis.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stumble</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stumble
<hw>Stum"ble</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A trip in walking or
running.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A blunder; a failure; a fall from
rectitude.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>One <qex>stumble</qex> is enough to deface the character of an
honorable life.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stumbler</ent>⟦br⟧
